observations.recommendation:
Management through the City Accountant analyze and conduct a thorough review of the dormant AP, retrieve pertinent supporting documents and check/validate the existence of actual claimants by sending confirmations prior to the reversion of these outstanding payables; and if the transactions cannot be substantiated with necessary documents and the payable accounts are found to be non-existing due to the absence of identified valid claimants, the funds intended for the said obligations shall be adjusted and reverted to the unappropriated surplus in accordance with the pertinent provisions of P.D. No. 1445;

Effect the necessary adjusting entries reclassify other payables erroneously recorded in the AP following the proposed adjusting journal entry; 


Analyze the existence of negative balances and make necessary adjusting entries in the book of accounts to correct the reported balance of the AP.

The City Mayor, Budget Officer and the City Accountant: 

Establish ways to improve the cash position such as, but not limited to, efficient revenue collection and adoption of effective austerity measures;

Review, prioritize and update the programs, activities and projects taking into consideration the total cash available for their implementation;

Hire qualified personnel to perform the monitoring and reconciliation duties; and


Conduct periodic reconciliation of records within and between the Budget and Accounting Offices.

Management improve their compliance with the guidelines so that adequate safeguard and effective/efficient utilization of the funds is ensured, by implementing the following courses of action:

Ensure that future receipts of FA are covered with appropriate MOA specifically providing guidelines for project implementation and reporting;

Require the City Treasurer to transfer the Financial Assistance (FA) that were deposited in the GF to the Trust Fund account and that future receipts of FA with specific purpose be properly deposited in the Agency’s trust account;




Require the City Accountant and the City Treasurer to return the unexpended balances of the FAs and proceed to submit the liquidation report to the SA; and

Take appropriate action for FAs in which the stated purpose became no longer implementable/executable either by returning the same to the SA or obtain similar approval from appropriate government agency to apply the fund to other purpose so as to ensure optimum utilization of the funds instead of being held idle.

The City Mayor, as the Chairperson of the LSB, and the Budget Officer: 

Prepare and submit the SEF Budget within the reglementary period which shall be presented by program, activity and project, by allotment class and per school including the target beneficiary schools;

Explain why the approved SEF budget was not fully supported with proposed expenditures;

Prepare the necessary, proper, complete and accurate data and information as basis in the preparation of budget that is compliant with Sections 4 and 5 of the Joint Circular; and

Explain the expenditures spent in excess of the approved SEF Budget and submit supporting documents relative thereto.

Management direct the City Accountant to record;

The noted costs incurred as addition to Asset. 




The cost of major repairs and improvements of existing PPE as part of the asset account.   The nature of expenses must be properly weighed and examined, if it involves major repair or improvement even if the same is for existing infrastructure, it should be recorded as an Asset.  Repairs and Maintenance Expense account is only for expenses involving minor repairs which do not entail significant improvement to the existing PPE.

Management look for an available area at the City Hall premises that can be used as warehouse or stockroom.  If not feasible, to construct a new structure for inventory safekeeping so that centralized inventory keeping and management will be implemented and proper inventory processes will be followed using the procedures laid down in Section 122, Chapter 7, Volume 1 of NGAS for LGUs.

The City Accountant immediately stop the practice of recording purchased inventories as outright expense but to record it first to an inventory account even if directly issued to end-users; 

The City Accountant to prepare the SLC per department pending the implementation of the centralized inventory management system; 


The designated supply officers in each department prepare and maintain the stock cards and to submit an inventory of supplies taken into account the items used during the month and the balance to be validated and consolidated by the GSO as a control measure in the usage and purchases of inventories. Subsequently, submit the report to the CAO for recording of issuance per department;

The designated supply officers per department in coordination with the GSO conduct the semi-annual physical inventory of supplies and materials and to submit the reports on time to the Audit Team.

Management use the eNGAS because of the aforementioned features which are not available in the system currently being used by the Accounting Office.

Management also to:

Direct the Accountant to start working on the data build-up and beginning    balances which are necessary for the immediate installation and use of the eNGAS;

Hire encoders, preferably with Accounting background, to speed up the data    build-up and beginning balances, as well as the encoding of transactions to the System, until a parallel test shall have been conducted;

provide the Accounting Office with a separate server to ensure the efficiency of the System and to safeguard its database.

The City Government to:

Collect from the retired personnel their outstanding liabilities;

Require the withholding of salaries or other compensation due the persons liable including those who signed the clearance of retired personnel in satisfaction of the disallowances or charges as mandated under COA Circular 2009-006.

Management maximize the utilization of City Wide Surveillance System by assigning a technical personnel to take charge watching the footage of the camera so that all the supposed benefits obtainable therefrom will be fully enjoyed by the City such as immediate detection of crimes;

Observe the prudent way of spending by avoiding any undertaking that entail substantial amount of government funds without getting the benefits commensurate to the amount spent;

Submit explanation/justification why the location of radio antenna not strategically positioned to minimize the cost thereof otherwise instruct those found accountable thereof to pay ₱436,680.00 representing the excess cost of antenna installed at St. Joseph Parish.

Submit breakdown of approved agency estimate for evaluation.

Management demand from those parties where payments were made to refund the amount paid to them and/or from City officials responsible thereto because as officials of a government agency they are responsible that government resources are managed, expended or utilized in accordance with law and regulations and safeguarded against loss or wastage through illegal or improper disposition, with a view to ensuring efficiency, economy and effectiveness in the operations of government; 

Refrain from paying claims for lot acquisitions affected by the implementation of the City’s development projects if subject properties are involved in ownership issues unless the subject concerns are properly addressed ensuring that the interest of the government is fully protected;

Conduct impartial investigation and institute appropriate sanctions against those responsible for the irregular act.

We recommended and the Acting City Accountant agreed to:
a) Request directly from the bank copies of bank statements of accounts not yet enrolled in the system to prepare the BRS and reflect the accurate and reliable Cash-in-Bank balance in the financial statements;
b) Comply with the requirements of LBP and DBP in the enrolment of other accounts to obtain copies of bank statements at the earliest possible time to avoid delayed preparation of monthly BRS;
c) Prepare the Bank Reconciliation Statements for all bank accounts pursuant to Item 3.2 of COA Circular No. 96-011 to verify the correctness and validity of recorded entries in the general ledger and bank statements on time; and
d) Ensure the submission of monthly BRS of all bank accounts to the Audit Team within the prescribed period.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management:
Establish ways to improve the cash position such as, but not limited to, efficient revenue collection and adoption of effective austerity measures;
Review, prioritize and update the programs, activities and projects taking into consideration the total cash available for their implementation;
Hire qualified personnel to perform the monitoring and reconciliation duties; and
Instruct the Budget and Accounting Offices to conduct periodic reconciliation of records within and among these offices.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the:
City Administrator to strictly implement the existing City Ordinance No. 95 s.2024 to enforce collection of stall rental;
City Legal Office in coordination with City Tourism Office to obtain lists of actual occupants in the Skate Park to facilitate the execution of the lease contracts to establish them as registered lessees;
City Treasurer to enforce the collection of stall rentals from the occupants upon execution of lease contracts, and regularly bill registered lessees and submit reports of delinquency to the City Accountant for increase efficiency.

City Accountant review carefully the request for cash advances for salaries, honorarium and other similar payments to ensure that the amount to be cash advanced is equal to the net amount of payroll for the pay period;

City Treasurer and the City Administrator stop the practice of transferring cash advances to another officers or employees.  Disbursement and liquidations are done by the person who were granted the cash advance; and


City Accountant direct the officials and employees who have unliquidated cash advances to liquidate immediately, otherwise, withhold their salary pursuant to Item 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002.

Management through the Licensing Officer and the City Treasurer:  

Finalize the roadmap for shifting from manual to automated business permits processing to ensure its smooth and successful transition. The transition plan should detail the key activities, process stakeholders, expected results/outputs and timelines for the implementation;

Consider setting up an appointment system where applicants are requested to come at designated dates and time to prevent the build-up of applicants at the Business One Stop Shop (BOSS) and address manpower constraints;

Strengthen barangay involvement during the conduct of the BOSS and encourage the Barangay Sanggunian to enact an ordinance allowing the City to accept applications, process, collect fees and issue clearances relative to barangay business clearance consistent with Section 11(f) of R.A. No. 11032; and

Consider revisiting the current steps and procedures, including reconfiguration of system controls, to eliminate redundant and circuitous processes and requirements and address the gaps in internal controls.

We recommended that:

The City Treasurer cancel all unclaimed checks which have become stale and present the cancelled checks in the Report of Checks Issued (RCI) after the last check issued and submit the original DVs and supporting documents to the City Accountant for the preparation of Journal Entry Voucher (JEV); 

Further, issue written notice to payees of checks at least one month before the checks become stale and immediately inform the City Accountant of any check cancellation to avoid the accumulation of outstanding checks in compliance with the requirement of Section 59 of the MNGAS for LGUs.

We recommended and the City Mayor agreed to:
Direct the BAC and the City Engineer to submit the appropriate supporting documents to prove that the projects were implemented and completed and the validity of the payments pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated         June 14, 2012;
Instruct the Inspectorate Team to examine and inspect thoroughly the accomplishments of the JO workers/contractors before and after the execution of the projects and provide attachments/documents to prove that the projects are implemented through the submission of pictures;
Require the City Accountant to thoroughly verify/scrutinize supporting documents attached to the disbursement vouchers before payments are made and the Implementing Office ensure the completeness of the project in accordance with the program of works before recommending the payment of the work accomplished; and
Henceforth, submit to the Audit Team copies of the Job Order contract within five working days from the execution of the contract pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009.

We recommended and the City Mayor, Budget Officer and the City Accountant agreed to:
Establish ways to improve the cash position such as, but not limited to, efficient revenue collection and adoption of effective austerity measures;
Review, prioritize and update the programs, activities and projects taking into consideration the total cash available for their implementation;
Hire qualified personnel to perform the monitoring and reconciliation duties; and
Conduct periodic reconciliation of records within and between the Budget and Accounting Offices.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and Management agreed to improve their compliance with the guidelines so that adequate safeguard and effective/efficient utilization of the funds is ensured, by implementing the following courses of action:
Ensure that future receipts of FA are covered with appropriate MOA specifically providing guidelines for project implementation and reporting;
Require the City Treasurer to transfer the FAs that were deposited in the General Fund to the Trust Fund account and that future receipts of FA with specific purpose be properly deposited in the Agency’s trust account;
Require the City Accountant and the City Treasurer to return the unexpended balances of the FAs and proceed to submit the liquidation report to the SA; and
Take appropriate action for FAs in which the stated purpose became no longer implementable/executable either by returning the same to the SA or obtain similar approval from appropriate government agency to apply the fund to other purpose so as to ensure optimum utilization of the funds instead of being held idle.
The City Accountant commented that they already transferred the financial assistance from the Bureau of the Treasury amounting to ₱33,034,410.85 on the Local Government Support Fund (LGSF) – Support to the Barangay Development Program of the National Task Force to End Local Communist Armed Conflict from the Trust Fund to the General Fund Books per entry made in January 2024.

We recommended and the City Mayor, as the Chairperson of the LSB, and the Budget Officer agreed to:
Prepare and submit the SEF Budget within the reglementary period which shall be presented by program, activity and project, by allotment class and per school including the target beneficiary schools;
Explain why the approved SEF budget was not fully supported with proposed expenditures;
Prepare the necessary, proper, complete and accurate data and information as basis in the preparation of budget that is compliant with Sections 4 and 5 of the Joint Circular; and
Explain the expenditures spent in excess of the approved SEF Budget and submit supporting documents relative thereto.
The School Division Superintendent and Co-chairperson of the Talisay City LSB explained that the LSB will dutifully comply with the submission of the SEF Budget for CY 2024 and the three-year program for CYs 2023 to 2026. It was further explained that in the preparation of SEF budget for CY 2023, the previous LSB was advised to streamline its budget, with enough allocation responding to emergency repairs of classrooms and printing of learning materials.  Nevertheless, the previous LSB duly submitted its Supplemental Budget Proposals to the City. As to the observed actual expenditures that exceeded the annual SEF budget for CY 2023, all these disbursements were duly supported by supplemental budget taken from the savings of other sources in the annual appropriation ordinance of the City.

We recommended and Management through the Licensing Officer and the City Treasurer agreed to:
Finalize the roadmap for shifting from manual to automated business permits processing to ensure its smooth and successful transition. The transition plan should detail the key activities, process stakeholders, expected results/outputs and timelines for the implementation;
Consider setting up an appointment system where applicants are requested to come at designated dates and time to prevent the build-up of applicants at the BOSS and address manpower constraints;
Strengthen barangay involvement during the conduct of the BOSS and encourage the Barangay Sanggunian to enact an ordinance allowing the City to accept applications, process, collect fees and issue clearances relative to barangay business clearance consistent with Section 11(f) of RA 11032; and
Consider revisiting the current steps and procedures, including reconfiguration of system controls, to eliminate redundant and unduly burdensome processes and requirements and address the gaps in internal controls.
During the exit conference, Management commented that the barangays had already issued an ordinance allowing the city to accept applications, process and collect fees, and issue clearances. As to the shifting from manual to automated business permits processing, there is an ongoing negotiation between the City and Landbank of the Philippines to link the payment to automated system of the City. The automated system shall cover the online assessment to online payment, including an option to print the temporary business permit.

We recommended that the City Mayor:

Direct DRRM and other Implementing Offices to properly utilize the LDRRMF pursuant to the requirements of RA No. 10121 and to use the LDRRM plan as basis in the execution of projects and programs and refrain charging unplanned projects under the Mitigation Fund unless the plan was revised;

Instruct the City Accountant to revert back to the unappropriated Surplus of the GF, the unexpended balance of the LDRRMF which could be utilized for other social services after enactment by the Sanggunian.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that:
The Inventory Committee prepare and submit the copy of RPCPPE to the Auditor in the prescribed format, not later than January 31 of each year. Moreover, ensure that the different columns therein are properly and completely filled out;
The Inventory Committee ensure that the account titles used in the RPCPPE are aligned in the LGU revised chart of accounts prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-009;
The Municipal Accounting Office and the Inventory Committee reconcile the difference between the PPE balances recorded in the books and in the RPCPPE;
The General Services Officer and the Municipal Accounting Office perform periodic reconciliation of Property Cards and Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards and ensure that all discrepancies are immediately investigated and addressed.

We recommended that:
The Accounting Unit evaluate each item of PPE to determine whether the new capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 shall be applied individually or in aggregate (such as in the case of Information and Communication Technology Equipment);
After such evaluation, determine the total amount of tangible items acquired and issued prior to CY 2022 with amounts from ₱15,000.00 to below ₱50,000.00 (as well as those below ₱15,000.00) which can be derecognized from the books;
Before any derecognition, the general services officer should be able to document first the accountability over these tangible items acquired and issued prior to CY 2022 with amounts from ₱15,000.00 to below ₱50,000.00 (as well as those below ₱15,000.00) through duly signed ICSs. The issuance of ICSs should be based on available but reliable alternative records of the LGU;
The Accounting Unit and the general services officer should coordinate and ensure that accountabilities over these properties were established before any derecognition;
The general services officer shall prepare and maintain the RegSPI for each class of semi-expendable property (low-valued items and high-value items) by fund; and
Prospectively, the general services officer secure and maintain the following:
The ICSs of the tangible items acquired and issued prior to CY 2022 with amounts from ₱15,000.00 to below ₱50,000.00 (as well as those below ₱15,000.00) which were derecognized from the books;
The ICSs of tangible items which meet the definition and recognition criteria of PPE but cost is below ₱50,000.00 (semi-expendable property) acquired during CY 2022 and onwards; and
The PARs of tangible items acquired during CY 2022 and onwards recognized as PPE.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Accountant:
Issue demand letters to:
Notify the concerned officials and employees of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advance/s. If settlement was not received, withhold from their salaries considering that they have been notified and given more adequate time to liquidate;
Official/s who already ended their term and employees of Department of Education to immediately cause the liquidation or settlement of the unliquidated balances;
Request the write-off of the unliquidated CAs of the dead, retired or absconded employee/s and also those which were lost due to fire following the guidelines and procedures on the write-off of dormant unliquidated CA in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;
Stop the practice of granting additional CA to concerned officials and employees unless the previous CA granted to them has been liquidated;
Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding CAs; and
Strictly comply with the provisions of the Circulars pertaining to CAs.

We recommended that:
In accordance with Item 13.1 of CSC-DBM JC No. 1 series of 2015, the LCE formulate and adopt internal rules and procedures on the rendition of overtime services which shall be aligned with relevant rules and regulations such as, but not limited to, COA Circular No. 2012-001 and CSC-DBM JC No. 1 series of 2015. In formulating and adopting such rules and procedures, the LCE should consider that as a general rule, the remuneration for overtime services shall be through CTO, in accordance with the guidelines under the CSC-DBM JCs No. 2, s. 2004 and No. 2-A. s. 2005.  However, the payment in cash of overtime services through Overtime Pay may be authorized only in exceptional cases when the application of CTO for all overtime hours would adversely affect the operations of the agency. Moreover, such internal rules and procedures shall endeavor uniformity of documents or forms to be used in connection with the rendition of overtime services;
The LCE ensure that the Request for Authority from LCE should be specific as to the names of personnel, the purpose or expected outputs, and the specific period of the overtime services (indicating the specific date, time, and number of hours). Most importantly, the LCE should warrant that only the requests for overtime services that are extremely necessary are granted considering the judicious use of government funds;
The LCE and other concerned personnel (from the Municipal Accounting Office and Municipal Treasurer’s Office) guarantee that payments for overtime services rendered shall be made only when:
Actual overtime services has been rendered and the period of overtime were in accordance with the Authority from LCE; and
The claims were supported with complete documentary requirements for overtime pay;
Without prejudice to the issuance of Notice of Suspension/Disallowance, the 10 regular employees of the LGU who were paid in excess of the limit prescribed for the overtime pay amounting to ₱457,539.71 refund immediately the said amounts to government funds;
The Municipal Accounting Office and the concerned employees who were paid for the rendition of overtime services submit immediately the lacking documents enumerated in Annex G for evaluation of the Audit Team, without prejudice to the issuance of Notice of Suspension/Disallowance; and
Prospectively, in compliance with Item 12.0 of CSC-DBM JC No. 1 series of 2015, the LCE ensure that the LGU submit to the DBM's Budget and Management Bureau or Regional Office concerned, copy furnished the CSC, the "Report on Overtime Services With Pay" using the template in Annex A of the JC on or before March 31 of every year.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Management:

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct complete physical count of its road networks in order to ascertain the existence of the balance of the account Road Networks;




Require the Designated General Services Officer to prepare a Report on Local Road Network, including a Road Map, at the end of accounting period and maintain the Local Road Network Property Card (LRNPC) for all roads and its components;

Direct the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit copy of the RPCPPE to the Auditor in prescribed format, not later than January 31 of each year. In the preparation of the report, the different column should be properly filled out to ensure that all items are properly identified and accounted for; and

Perform periodic reconciliation of property cards with the books of accounts to ensure that all discrepancies are immediately investigated, cleared and reconciled.

We recommended that the Management:

Require each AOs (the Collectors and the MT) to prepare and submit individual RAAFs; 

Ensure that consolidated RAAF resulted from the consolidation of all the AOs’ individual RAAFs;

Require the MT to ensure inclusion of checks in her individual RAAF and, accordingly, in the consolidated RAAF;

Immediately verify the unaccounted ORs by providing details as to when said ORs where issued to payors and remitted to the Liquidating Officer (LO)/MT; and 

Ensure preparation and submission of these RAAFs in accordance with the cited regulations.

We recommended that the Management:

Ensure that additional CAs are drawn only after the liquidation of previous CAs;


Strictly and religiously monitor the submission of Liquidation Reports/Report of Disbursements for the timely accounting thereof in order to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding CAs;

Ensure that CAs are drawn in the name of the DO. Moreover, preparation of liquidation documents as well as the maintenance of Cashbook be done by the DO;

Review thoroughly, completely and carefully the reconciliation of records in order to avoid omission of transactions pertaining to CAs and liquidation. Moreover, update the Cashbook and SL with regard to the above-mentioned unrecorded transactions; and

Ensure compliance with existing laws, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of CAs.

We recommended that the Management:

Ensure submission of all perfected contracts and its supporting documents for auditorial and technical review to the COA within five working days from the date of perfection of such contracts;

Strictly check the completeness of the perfected contracts and its supporting documents before its submission to the COA in order to avoid delays in the conduct of the auditorial and technical review;

Direct the concerned Implementing Offices such as, but not limited to, Municipal Engineering Office (MEO), Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Management Office (MDRRMO), and others, to promptly submit the relevant documents to the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to facilitate its timely submission for auditorial and technical review to the COA; and

Subject to the evaluation of the LGU and of the availability of its funds, consider the designation of additional support staff to the Bids and Award Committee (BAC)in order to hasten and avoid delay in the submission of perfected contracts and its supporting documents for auditorial and technical review.

We recommended that Management:

a.	Adopt the provisions of the austerity program of the government by reducing the cost of expenses in the hiring of job orders and repair and maintenance of motor vehicles/heavy equipment, and others to ensure stability of its fiscal resources;

b.	Prioritize the outstanding payables to BIR, GSIS, Pag-IBIG and Philhealth to avoid incurrence of penalties and surcharges and for member beneficiaries to avail of the privileges and benefits due them; 

c.	Review the City’s programs/projects and implement only those that are critical, urgent and necessary; and

d.	Direct the City Treasurer to explain in writing the occurrence of negative Cash balances which is an indication of poor cash management.

We recommend that Management use the eNGAS because of the aforementioned features which are not available in the system currently being used by the Accounting Office.

We also recommend that Management:

direct the Accountant to start working on the data build-up and beginning    balances which are necessary for the immediate installation and use of the eNGAS;

hire encoders, preferably with Accounting background, to speed up the data    build-up and beginning balances, as well as the encoding of transactions to the System, until a parallel test shall have been conducted;

provide the Accounting Office with a separate server to ensure the efficiency of the System and to safeguard its database.

Conduct an impartial investigation and institute appropriate sanctions against those personnel found responsible in the commission of such unlawful act;
Consider blacklisting the supplier for the violation of the contract and for the refund of the cost of undelivered items;
Submit a written explanation why the above-mentioned claims were processed and paid despite of undelivered items, otherwise subject claims shall be suspended and/or disallowed in audit and shall hold all those who authorized the payment as jointly and severally liable of the amount disbursed;
Direct the BAC to explain why they resorted to the shopping mode of procurement instead of public bidding;
Scrutinize subsequent transactions to prevent paying fraudulent claims.

Maximize the utilization of City Wide Surveillance System by assigning a technical personnel to take charge watching the footage of the camera so that all the supposed benefits obtainable therefrom will be fully enjoyed by the City such as immediate detection of crimes;
Observe the prudent way of spending by avoiding any undertaking that entail substantial amount of government funds without getting the benefits commensurate to the amount spent;
Submit explanation/justification why the location of radio antenna not strategically positioned to minimize the cost thereof otherwise instruct those found accountable thereof to pay ₱436,680.00 representing the excess cost of antenna installed at St. Joseph Parish.
Submit breakdown of approved agency estimate for evaluation.

Demand from those parties where payments were made to refund the amount paid to them and/or from City officials responsible thereto because as officials of a government agency they are responsible that government resources are managed, expended or utilized in accordance with law and regulations and safeguarded against loss or wastage through illegal or improper disposition, with a view to ensuring efficiency, economy and effectiveness in the operations of government; 

Refrain from paying claims for lot acquisitions affected by the implementation of the City’s development projects if subject properties are involved in ownership issues unless the subject concerns are properly addressed ensuring that the interest of the government is fully protected; 

Conduct impartial investigation and institute appropriate sanctions against those responsible for the irregular act.

