Strictly check the completeness of the perfected contracts and its supporting documents before its submission to the COA in order to avoid delays in the conduct of the auditorial and technical review;
Direct the concerned Implementing Offices such as, but not limited to, MEO, MDRRMO, and others, to promptly submit the relevant documents to the BAC to facilitate its timely submission for auditorial and technical review to the COA; and
Subject to the evaluation of the LGU and of the availability of its funds, consider the designation of additional support staff to the BAC in order to hasten and avoid delay in the submission of perfected contracts and its supporting documents for auditorial and technical review.

We recommended that Management:
Submit an amended LDRRMFIP that includes the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years in conformity with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-002;
Submit the SP Resolutions to authorize the disbursements in the amount of ₱20,351,895.86 charged against the unexpended balance of DRRM Fund of the previous years;
Submit an explanation on the delayed transfer of the CY 2020 unexpended DRRM Fund to the Trust Fund; and
Immediately submit the Reports on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF for CY 2021 and henceforth, observe the timely submission of the said report.

We recommended that:
The City Mayor include in the General Fund budget the requirements for personnel services, other maintenance and operating expenses and capital outlay of the CDRR office pursuant to the provision of Item 4.2 of JMC No. 2014-1 dated April 4, 2014;
The City Mayor discontinue the practice of charging wages of Job Order personnel assigned in the different offices, gasoline and maintenance of vehicles against the LDRRMF unless such expenditures are in connection with the implementation of LDRRM programs and projects;
The CDDRM Council adhere strictly to the guidelines in the allocation and utilization of the LDRRMF as prescribed under NDRRMC-DBM and DILG JMC No. 2013-01 dated March 25, 2013; and
The City Accountant and the City Budget Officer properly review expenses charged against the LDRRMF and refrain from utilizing the fund for program, projects and activities not pertaining to disaster-related activities or not in accordance with the primary purpose for which the fund was established.

We recommended that the City Health Officer:
Obtain records of the total number of vaccines allocated to the City from the PHO;
Install electronic tracking system to facilitate recording, monitoring and utilization of donations in kind;
Furnish the Accounting Office with the inventory of COVID-19 vaccines, in relation to its COVID-19 Vaccination Program; and
The City Accountant record all remaining vaccines in the books in accordance with Paragraph 96 of IPSAS 23.

We recommended the Management to:

Issue demand letters to: 
Notify the concerned officials and employees of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated CAs. If settlement was not received, withhold from their salaries considering that they have been notified and given more adequate time to liquidate; and

Official/s who already ended their term and employees of Department of Education to immediately cause the liquidation or settlement of the unliquidated balances;

Request the write-off of the unliquidated CAs of the dead, retired or absconded employee/s following the guidelines and procedures on the write-off of dormant unliquidated CA in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;

Stop the practice of granting additional cash advance to concerned officials and employees unless the previous CA granted to them has been liquidated; 



Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding CAs; and


Strictly comply with the provisions of the Circulars pertaining to CAs.

observations.managementAction:
In its Reply, the Management explained that the preparation/formulation of the GAD Plan and Budget for CY 2021 was coordinated to different offices with regards to their proposed PPAs responsive to gender related issues and concerns. However, since the implementation of GPB for CY 2021 is still at the height of the pandemic, there were PPAs realigned for other urgent priorities to address the emerging effect of COVID-19 pandemic. Further, because of limited yearly GAD Fund allocation, PPAs which requires continuing intervention were considered, thus, sex disaggregated data/information on GAD issues had already been reflected in the prior year’s GPB.

Nonetheless, the Management agreed to implement the recommendations. In view of this, the Management committed to take the following courses of action:

Use of the revised forms for GPB and GAD AR;

Be more compliant with the guidelines on GAD;

Be analytical on PPAs that can be charged to the GAD Budget; and

Ensure that sex-disaggregation and other relevant data/information shall be used as basis in determining gender issues and mandate needed to be addressed/prioritized.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Ensure submission of all perfected contracts and its supporting documents for auditorial and technical review to the COA within five working days from the date of perfection of such contracts;

Strictly check the completeness of the perfected contracts and its supporting documents before its submission to the COA in order to avoid delays in the conduct of the auditorial and technical review;

Direct the concerned Implementing Offices such as, but not limited to, MEO, MDRRMO, and others, to promptly submit the relevant documents to the BAC to facilitate its timely submission for auditorial and technical review to the COA; and

Subject to the evaluation of the LGU and of the availability of its funds, consider the designation of additional support staff to the BAC in order to hasten and avoid delay in the submission of perfected contracts and its supporting documents for auditorial and technical review.

We reiterated previous recommendations that Management: 

Instruct all accountable officers concerned to immediately liquidate all cash advances and that current CAs for travel should first be settled before new ones be allowed to the same accountable officers in compliance with COA Circular Nos. 97-002 and 2012-004;

Exert extra efforts to recover outstanding CAs from Accountable officers who are no longer in the service nor connected with the Municipality;


Observe strictly the guidelines on the granting, utilization and liquidation of CAs provided in Sections 4 and 5 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; and

Resort to the withholding of salaries of Accountable Officers and employees if they still fail or persistently refuse to settle/liquidate their CAs.

We recommended that Management direct the City Accountant to: 

Analyze all the receivables from NGOs/POs that are dormant, long outstanding and unsubstantiated for proper disposition, otherwise request for write-off;
Retrieve MOAs to determine the conditions of the grants;
Maintain Subsidiary Ledgers for receivables to monitor collections of loan amortizations from concerned NGOs/POs; and
Make representations with the Focal Persons to facilitate the liquidations thereof.

We reiterated our recommendation that the City Mayor:

Require the City Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of physical count of all City’s PPE so they could submit the complete Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) not later than January 31 of each year pursuant to Section 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;

Require the City Accountant and the GSO to implement regular reconciliation of their records and undertake specific measures to eliminate the discrepancies between the two records; and; 

Require the City Accountant and the GSO to maintain updated PPE ledger and property cards, respectively so reconciliation of the two records could be done easily.

We recommended that the City Mayor and the City Accountant:

Enforce immediate settlement of all outstanding cash advances totaling ₱4,295,315.25, especially those intended for special purposes pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-02 dated February 10, 1997; 

Ascertain that no additional cash advances shall be granted to officials and employees with outstanding cash advances pursuant to the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and Item 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 22, 1997;

Ensure that cash advance granted shall be limited to the requirements for two months pursuant to Item 4.4.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 22, 1997;

Send   demand   letters to officials and employees who have long outstanding cash advances to settle the overdue amounts within a specific period; and 

Otherwise, effect the withholding of   their   salaries   pursuant to Item 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 until such time that the cash advances are fully settled.

We recommended that the City Mayor as Chairman of the Local School Board:

Refrain from utilizing the Special Education Fund for trainings, seminars and other school activities since they are not allowable expenses to be charged against the Fund pursuant to Item 4.0 of DepEd, DBM and DILG Joint Circular (JC) No. 1, series of 2017     January 17, 2017; 

Allocate and utilize the SEF on the priority programs and projects provided under Section 272 of RA No. 7160;

Discontinue the grant of cash advances to Special Disbursing Officers for the procurement needs funded by the SEF and adhere to the regulation that all payments must be made by check pursuant to Section 40 of the MNGAS for LGUs and guideline no. 2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; and

Authorize only the City Treasurer to disburse funds from the SEF pursuant to the budget prepared and in accordance with existing rules and regulations provided under Section 99 of RA No. 7160 or the Local Government Code.

