We recommended and Management agreed to require the Head of the Procuring Entity (HOPE) to:
Create an inventory committee to undertake the physical count of all inventories to establish the existence and accuracy of the inventory account balances and prepare and submit the required RPCI;
Strengthen controls over the inventory requiring the personnel in charge to prepare the RIS and SSMI to record the expenditures, maintain and update subsidiary ledgers and stock cards to facilitate reconciliation and adjustments; and henceforth regularly reconcile their respective records on all inventory accounts so that any discrepancy is immediately verified and adjusted.

We recommend that the City Accountant:
make the necessary correcting journal entries in order to re-classify all the fund transfers to their proper account classification so as to fairly present the financial statements;
conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis, and validation of the existence of the receivables, unliquidated cash advances, and fund transfers and prepare the necessary adjusting entry/ies for the recognition of the computed impairment in accordance with the Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standards;
prepare aging of dormant receivables, unliquidated cash advances and fund transfers on a quarterly basis to support the request for write-off, if warranted.

We recommend that the City Government:
Direct the BAC Secretariat/Technical Working Group to perform its functions in assisting the BAC especially in the conduct of the post-qualification activities and in the preparation of the post -qualification summary report;
Require the BAC to submit the post-qualification summary reports.

We recommend that the City Government:
require the Bids and Awards Committee to explain in writing why the Bidding Documents for the procurement of security services did not include the General and Special Conditions of the Contract;
direct the City Legal Officer to review the contract, as well as the bidding documents, executed between the City and the Security Agency and take appropriate curative legal measures to protect the interest of the City;
direct the Bids and Awards Committee to include in the Bidding Documents the General and Special Conditions of the Contract in the future public biddings especially to procurement of goods of special nature such as security and janitorial services.

We recommend that Management:
direct the accountable officer to settle immediately her cash advances in order to avoid administrative liability;
direct the special disbursing officers to explain why they passed on their cash advances to other persons who were not accountable thereto;
direct the special disbursing officers to explain why it took them 100 to 198 days to liquidate their cash advances; and stop the practice of granting cash advances for travel to a person other than the employee who is authorized/issued travel order.

We recommend that Management:
direct the City Treasurer and the City Accountant to release the shares of the component barangays in the Real Property Taxes collected without need of any further action on a quarterly basis within five days after the end of each quarter;
direct the City Treasurer and City Accountant to facilitate the processing of these proceeds without requiring a barangay resolution requesting for the release of said funds

We recommend that Management:
direct the City Treasurer to comply with Article 2, Section 62 of the Talisay City Revised Revenue Code of 2011 which requires suppliers and contractors who wish to transact business in Talisay City to secure a Mayor’s permit;
secure a list of business establishments from the barangays who issued clearances to those who wish to operate in the locality to help the City Government track business establishments operating without the required business permits and licenses.

We recommend and Management agreed to instruct the City Treasurer to:
require from the suppliers or contractors, the submission of audited financial statements, Sworn Statement of Gross Sales or Receipts (GSR) or Bureau of Internal Revenue (BIR) quarterly or monthly payment reports such as VAT payments and percentages taxes with the corresponding receipts evidencing payments thereof in order to come up with a correct assessment;
enforce payment of delinquent taxes before issuance of a Mayor’s permit;
coordinate with the Business Permit Licensing Office regarding the non-inclusion of business establishments who have paid the regulatory business fees and taxes in their List of Issued Business Permits; and
make sure application forms for business permit are completely and correctly accomplished and that the CTO personnel who made the assessment print and sign his/her name.

We recommend that the City Government:
direct the various offices and departments involved in procurement to identify the bottlenecks in the process in order to achieve effectiveness and efficiency in the delivery of the goods and services to the end-users within a reasonable time;
instruct the General Services Office and the Accounting Department to work as partners in processing the payments to suppliers within the payment terms.

We recommend that Management:
direct the Bids and Awards Committee to submit a written explanation why the contract was awarded to an ineligible bidder;
direct the Bids and Awards Committee to conduct all bidding process  strictly in accordance with the law;
conduct further investigation and consider blacklisting the contractor for its failure to complete the project;
direct the City Engineering Office to conduct inspection and determine if the percentage of completion reaches 70% as claimed, otherwise request for refund for the excess payment.

We recommend that the City Government:
direct the Bids and Awards Committee to explain in writing why the above discussed contracts were awarded to ineligible bidders;
remind the Bids and Awards Committee of its duty to carry out the procurement process strictly in accordance with the law and with utmost transparency;
require the winning bidder to submit the lacking documentary requirements for eligibility checking;
direct the Accounting Division to require the submission of PhilGEPS registration number in all public bidding procurement and in the alternative modes of procurement mentioned in Annex H, Appendix A of the IRR of RA 9184. We further recommend that all payments to suppliers be duly supported with the documentary requirements under COA Circular No. 2012-001.

